President Trump arrived in Rome, Italy as part of his first international trip. He visited the Vatican and had bilateral meetings with President Sergio Mattarella and Prime Minister Paolo Gentiloni of Italy. They discussed the alliance between the United States and Italy, as well as priorities in defense cooperation, counterterrorism, and efforts to deny terrorists safe havens. President Trump thanked Italy for its contributions to global counterterrorism efforts, including its participation in the Global Coalition to Counter ISIS. They also discussed goals for the upcoming G7 Summit in Taormina. The President and First Lady then departed Rome for Brussels, Belgium for the NATO Leaders Meeting.